    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:c2e92b60-1385-478b-aa47-eb9e20c500fa",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-description</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-description"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} is a 58-year-old woman with a warm, unhurried manner and a rounded, apple-shaped figure. She stands at 5'4\" (163 cm) and weighs approximately 84 kg, giving her a BMI of around 31.5. Her complexion is olive-toned, and she wears reading glasses perched on the end of her nose. She speaks with a slight Southern accent and carries a worn canvas tote bag full of grocery coupons, church bulletins, and her blood glucose logbook.\n\n{patientName} works part-time as a school librarian in a small suburban town, a job she has held for nearly two decades and loves dearly. She enjoys organizing book fairs, recommending novels to students, and tending to her vegetable garden on weekends. She lives with her husband of 32 years in a tidy ranch-style home. They have two adult children and three grandchildren whom she visits regularly. Her social life revolves around a local quilting circle that meets every Thursday evening and Sunday church services.\n\nShe was diagnosed with Type 2 diabetes mellitus about six years ago after a routine workplace health screening revealed a fasting glucose of 186 mg/dL. She admits to struggling with dietary discipline — she has a known fondness for sweet tea and homemade biscuits — but has made consistent efforts to walk 20–30 minutes most mornings. She monitors her blood glucose at home three to four times per week and brings a handwritten log to every clinic appointment.\n\nClinically, {patientName} reports mild fatigue in the late afternoon, occasional increased thirst, and mild nocturia (once per night). She denies chest pain, shortness of breath, visual disturbances, numbness, or foot ulcers. Her blood pressure has been borderline elevated on prior visits. She is generally cheerful and cooperative during examinations but occasionally expresses anxiety about \"ending up like her mother,\" who suffered serious complications from diabetes.\n\nHer current lifestyle includes a modestly calorie-controlled diet, occasional lapses with carbohydrate-rich foods, and daily low-intensity walking. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol only occasionally at social gatherings — typically a single glass of wine. She does not use recreational drugs. She manages her medications reliably and keeps all scheduled follow-up appointments."
          }
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "fullUrl": "urn:uuid:7d665b13-6802-47f6-b5d7-0692e96af291",
      "resource": {
        "resourceType": "Communication",
        "status": "completed",
        "text": {
          "status": "generated",
          "div": "<div xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\">patient-history</div>"
        },
        "category": [
          {
            "coding": [
              {
                "system": "urn:virpat:fhir:doc-type",
                "code": "patient-history"
              }
            ]
          }
        ],
        "subject": {
          "reference": "urn:uuid:11111111-1111-4111-8111-111111111111"
        },
        "payload": [
          {
            "contentString": "{patientName} was first diagnosed with Type 2 diabetes mellitus six years ago following an incidental workplace health screening. She has no prior hospitalizations related to diabetes. Her past medical history is notable for mild hypertension diagnosed three years ago, managed with Ramipril, and hyperlipidemia identified concurrently with her diabetes diagnosis. She has no known history of coronary artery disease, stroke, peripheral neuropathy, or chronic kidney disease. She underwent a routine diabetic retinal eye examination two years ago, which was normal.\n\n{patientName} has never smoked and consumes alcohol only occasionally. She is postmenopausal and underwent natural menopause at age 52. Her BMI of 31.5 places her in the obese category, which is a recognized contributing factor to her insulin resistance. She has received dietary counseling on two occasions through her primary care clinic and is aware of carbohydrate counting but inconsistently applies it. She has no prior surgical history of relevance. She takes her medications regularly and denies any history of hypoglycemic episodes requiring assistance. Family history is significant for Type 2 diabetes and cardiovascular disease on the maternal side."
          }
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
